text:
Let‚Äôs be honest‚ÄîCrying to Jahunaam is basically your angry neighborhood WhatsApp uncle who discovered a webcam. He yells a lot, throws in some Arabic words to sound deep, and repeats the same tired lines about how Pakistan is ‚Äúpure‚Äù and minorities disappearing is ‚Äúnormal.‚Äù Normal? Mate, your moral compass is so broken it thinks genocide is a GPS setting.

Let‚Äôs start with qualifications‚Äîwhat qualifications? This guy isn‚Äôt a geopolitical analyst, economist, historian, sociologist, or Islamic scholar. He‚Äôs just a loudmouth with Wi-Fi. If your car breaks down, you call a mechanic. If you want to understand complex issues like international law, population collapse, or religious persecution, maybe don‚Äôt trust the guy who thinks laughing at Hindu girls being abducted is some kind of punchline.

On geopolitics, he talks like he‚Äôs read one chapter of a high school textbook and skipped all the footnotes. Real analysts talk about treaties, strategic depth, resource access, demographic trends, or China‚Äôs Belt and Road. He just screams ‚ÄúGhazwa-e-Hind!‚Äù like a broken record. If that‚Äôs geopolitics, then I‚Äôm the Prime Minister of Wakanda.

Economically? Don‚Äôt even go there. He couldn‚Äôt tell the difference between a fiscal deficit and a hole in his own narrative. While Pakistan sinks under IMF loans and can‚Äôt even pay for basic imports, he‚Äôs busy boasting about nuclear weapons‚Äîas if you can eat uranium parathas for breakfast. His economic worldview is basically: ‚ÄúBlame India, praise Turkey, and quote imaginary golden age statistics that never existed.‚Äù

Morally? This is where it gets sick. Laughing off ethnic cleansing isn‚Äôt edgy‚Äîit‚Äôs pathetic. Minorities in Pakistan have dropped from over 20% in 1947 to less than 3% today. That‚Äôs not ‚Äúnatural,‚Äù that‚Äôs cleansing. When you excuse that by saying ‚ÄúPakistan was made for Muslims,‚Äù what you‚Äôre really saying is, ‚ÄúWe don‚Äôt believe in basic human rights if you‚Äôre not one of us.‚Äù If ISIS had a PR intern, they‚Äôd probably sound like him.

And Islamically? Please. He‚Äôs not a scholar, he‚Äôs a salesman‚Äîselling fear, rage, and victimhood wrapped in religious packaging. Real Islamic scholars talk about justice, truth, and protecting the oppressed. He talks about dominance, revenge, and hiding behind the cloak of ‚Äúummah‚Äù to justify tyranny. That‚Äôs not piety‚Äîthat‚Äôs political Islam with a fake beard and a YouTube channel.

He‚Äôs not a thought leader, he‚Äôs a thoughtless follower of the worst kind of ideology. The kind that thrives on taqiyya, distraction, and moral double standards. The kind that defends the indefensible and gaslights entire communities into silence.

So let‚Äôs call it for what it is. He‚Äôs not misunderstood. He‚Äôs not brave. He‚Äôs not deep. He‚Äôs just another Islamist grifter pretending to be a scholar. The only thing he‚Äôs qualified to lead is a group therapy session for insecure men with superiority complexes.

Don‚Äôt fall for the drama. Don‚Äôt give clowns like him your mindspace. And if you want to understand real geopolitics, history, morality, or religion‚Äîread books, listen to real experts, and keep your humanity intact. Because once you start laughing at the suffering of others, you‚Äôve not only lost the argument‚Äîyou‚Äôve lost your soul.

text:
Pakistan‚Äôs inability to sustain a conventional war with India for even seven days is a conclusion grounded in military logistics, strategic doctrine, economic capacity, and international political constraints. From a military-political analysis perspective, the imbalance between the two states is not merely numerical but systemic.

First, in terms of defense logistics and warfighting sustainability, Pakistan maintains what military analysts term a ‚Äúshort-war posture.‚Äù Open-source intelligence, including reports from former Pakistani defense officials and analyses by think tanks such as RAND and SIPRI, confirm that Pakistan‚Äôs conventional war reserves‚Äîparticularly in ammunition, fuel, and spare parts‚Äîare calibrated for a high-intensity conflict lasting 7 to 10 days at most. This doctrinal limitation arises from both resource scarcity and an implicit reliance on early international mediation or nuclear escalation to deter or truncate Indian conventional advances.

In contrast, India has invested heavily in building a ‚ÄúProlonged War Doctrine,‚Äù with forward-deployed ammunition, integrated logistics networks, and indigenous production through entities like DRDO and the Ordnance Factory Board (now corporatized). India‚Äôs acquisitions, such as the S-400 air defense system, along with significant upgrades in logistics infrastructure along the western border, enhance its ability to fight a sustained two-front conflict, should the need arise. These factors are embedded within India‚Äôs strategic doctrine of ‚Äúmulti-domain preparedness,‚Äù which positions it for both attritional and high-mobility warfare over extended periods.

Economically, the disparity is stark and consequential. According to the 2023 SIPRI Military Expenditure Database, India‚Äôs defense budget was approximately $76 billion, placing it third globally, whereas Pakistan‚Äôs was around $10‚Äì11 billion. More crucially, Pakistan‚Äôs economy, with persistent twin deficits, minimal foreign reserves (at times covering less than two months of imports), and dependency on IMF bailouts, lacks the fiscal space to support a large-scale war effort. War expenditures in modern contexts are not confined to battlefield logistics‚Äîthey involve long-term costs in procurement, civil defense, economic mobilization, and political capital, all of which Pakistan lacks the bandwidth to absorb. Political economists note that Pakistan‚Äôs military expenditure, which comprises over 17% of the federal budget, is already politically and socially unsustainable, given the simultaneous crises in health, food security, and public infrastructure.

Politically, Pakistan operates in a constrained international environment. Its historical overreliance on asymmetric warfare and its associations with non-state actors have diminished its standing in Western defense forums. The FATF grey-listing (2018‚Äì2022), repeated U.S. criticism of its duplicity on counterterrorism, and the shifting Gulf alignment toward economic pragmatism over ideological patronage have further isolated Pakistan diplomatically. In contrast, India enjoys strategic partnerships with the United States, France, Israel, and Russia, and participates in multilateral security dialogues like the Quad, giving it both diplomatic insulation and military interoperability with advanced powers.

From a nuclear deterrence theory perspective, Pakistan‚Äôs ‚Äúfirst use‚Äù doctrine serves as a strategic equalizer. However, it also underscores its weakness in the conventional domain. The very reliance on nuclear rhetoric in response to Indian conventional superiority reflects Pakistan‚Äôs inability to sustain traditional military operations. No serious nuclear state views nuclear warfighting as a viable long-term strategy; rather, it is a last-resort deterrent, which, if employed, would lead to catastrophic retaliation.

In sum, the military-political calculus is clear: Pakistan lacks the economic resilience, logistical depth, and geopolitical alignment required to fight and sustain a conventional war against India for more than a few days. This asymmetry shapes the strategic restraint observed in Rawalpindi despite rhetorical posturing and underscores why Pakistan continues to rely on sub-conventional warfare and diplomatic internationalization rather than conventional engagement.

text:
@ You have to restrain your anger, because Allah says (interpretation of the meaning):

‚Äú‚Ä¶who repress anger, and who pardon men; verily, Allah loves Al-Muhsinoon (the good‚Äëdoers).‚Äù

[3:134]

‚ÄúAnd those who avoid the greater sins, and Al‚ÄëFawahish (illegal sexual intercourse), and when they are angry, they forgive.‚Äù

[42:37]

This is because when a person does not restrain his anger, he insults, curses, swears and hits. Anger may be a door to all kinds of evil. The Prophet (peace and blessings of Allah be upon him) often advised people not to get angry. Al-Bukhari narrated in al-Saheeh from Abu Hurayrah (may Allah be pleased with him) that a man said to the Prophet (peace and blessings of Allah be upon him), ‚ÄúAdvise me.‚Äù He said: ‚ÄúDo not get angry.‚Äù The man repeated his request several times, and he said, ‚ÄúDo not get angry.‚Äù

The Prophet (peace and blessings of Allah be upon him) regarded the one who controls himself when he is angry as being the strongest of men. Al-Bukhari narrated in al-Saheeh that the Messenger of Allah (peace and blessings of Allah be upon him) said: ‚ÄúThe strong man is not the one who can wrestle (fight); the strong man is the one who controls himself at the time of anger.‚Äù

If this is how Pakistan treats the Kashmiris it already governs, it‚Äôs no wonder many in Indian-administered Kashmir are skeptical.

Lastly, the idea that only ‚ÄúIndians push a narrative‚Äù is a political deflection. Indian citizens, including Kashmiris, have every right to discuss national issues. This isn‚Äôt about silencing Kashmiri voices‚Äîit‚Äôs about recognizing all Kashmiri voices, including those who don‚Äôt support separatism, who want peace, development, and dignity within a democratic India.

‚ÄúWallahi, this won‚Äôt go unanswered!‚Äù

Oh really? What are you going to do, mate‚Äîsend a strongly worded khutbah from Lagos? Please. India launches precision strikes on verified terror camps, and suddenly your voice goes from WhatsApp warrior to Jihadi Shakespeare. Meanwhile, not a peep from you when Hindu tourists get blown up during a pilgrimage by your ‚Äúfreedom fighters.‚Äù That‚Äôs not resistance‚Äîit‚Äôs cowardice in a suicide vest.

‚ÄúHindutva killing children!‚Äù Right, let‚Äôs be clear: the only people turning children into collateral are the ones hiding behind them. You know, those brave ‚Äúmujahideen‚Äù using mosques as missile depots and madrassas as human shields. Spare us the crocodile tears‚Äîyour moral compass is spinning like a fidget spinner during Ramadan.

‚ÄúModi‚Äôs destroying India!‚Äù Have you seen Pakistan lately? Your own backyard‚Äôs on fire, but you‚Äôre tweeting about the neighbor‚Äôs lawn. Pakistan can‚Äôt keep the lights on without a Chinese extension cord, but you‚Äôre busy diagnosing India‚Äôs democracy from your phone in Nigeria? That‚Äôs like a guy with no shoes giving fashion tips.

And let‚Äôs not forget the mandatory Israel and U.S. rant‚Äîclassic. Always the Jews and the Yankees. Mate, it‚Äôs not a conspiracy, it‚Äôs just that Pakistan backed the wrong side of history again, and now you‚Äôre all shouting into microphones from borrowed studios while Israel builds tech empires and India lands stuff on the Moon.

‚ÄúMuch love and prayers for Pakistan and Kashmir.‚Äù Cheers. I‚Äôm sure the ISI will print that on their next terror recruitment flyer. Meanwhile, the real Kashmiris are trying to get jobs, not jihad. They don‚Äôt want your hashtags‚Äîthey want peace.

Now stop pretending your selective outrage is activism. It‚Äôs just hypocrisy with Wi-Fi.
